Based on who they follow
\series default
: It's hard to directly do clustering on common users.
 But it is relatively easy to cluster those celebrities / influencers, they
 are most likely just has oen label --- either movie star, musician, or
 comupter scientist.
 So their labels are more 
\series bold
pure 
\series default
that common users.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Then we go back to the common users, to see what types of celebrities they
 follow
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Or we can even bring the number of likes or retweets for each celebrities,
 using this as a weight to mearue how strong / close this following relation
 is.
 So the following relation is no longer 0 or 1 anymore, it may be 0, 1,
 2, continous integers.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Data can be constructed like this: It is a matrix with rows as users, columns
 as celebrities.
 value equal to 1 if a user follow a celebrity, equal to 0 if not.
 OR the value is the total 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Pagerank to measure importance/influence of user
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The importance of a user depends on number of followers, and also depend
 on the importance of those followers.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If an influential celebrity A follows B, that means A endorses some of his
 impotant to him
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Pagerank algorithm is using this idea to measure how importance/influence
 of a point in the network.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The way it works is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Image you want to do a random work through all the social network, starting
 from point A, as A is following N people the probability that A travels
 to each followees 1/N.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then assume now we travel from A to B, then do a random walk to the people
 that B follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
You keep doing one millions of time, and it turned out the probability/number
 of times of getting to a certain point will converge to a steady value.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
That value is the score of the importance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the idea is: if the more people follow a point A, then it is easier to get
 their.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Path Find to Measure Importance of a User
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You can think about this problem as a path finding problem: How to find
 the shortest parth to travel from one user to another user.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If you randomly select two points in the scoial network, both A and B have
 no common firends in the real world, but they both follow one musician
 in Twitter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
You do this test millions times --- each time you randomly select two points
 and calculating the clost path.
 The more common trespassing / transiting points are those celebrities.
\end_layout

